## 3. Data Preprocessing

### 3.1 Merging ERA5 Pressure-Level Data
ERA5 pressure-level variables were **pivoted** from long format (one row per variable per pressure level) to wide format using `pandas.pivot_table`, creating columns like `r_500`, `t_700`, `u_850`, etc. Surface variables were merged separately, followed by an inner join with the TP precipitation data on [(valid_time, latitude, longitude)](file:///c:/Users/HYPER%20Computers/Downloads/a4.project.bilstm/app.py#53-59).

### 3.2 Cloudburst Label Definition
A sample is labelled as a **cloudburst (positive class = 1)** if precipitation exceeds the **95th percentile of the total precipitation distribution OR 20 mm/hr**, whichever is greater:

```
cloudburst_threshold = max(percentile_95(tp_mm), 20.0 mm/hr) = 20.00 mm/hr
```

This scientifically grounded threshold produced:
- **Positive (cloudburst) events:** 764 out of 61,998 (only **1.23%**)
- This severe **class imbalance** (82:1 ratio) is the central challenge of this problem.

### 3.3 Cyclical Time Feature Engineering
To help the model understand seasonality (monsoon season peaks in July–August), four cyclical features were derived from the timestamp using sine/cosine encoding — this avoids discontinuities at year/month boundaries:

```python
month_sin = sin(2π × month / 12)
month_cos = cos(2π × month / 12)
doy_sin   = sin(2π × day_of_year / 365)
doy_cos   = cos(2π × day_of_year / 365)
```

### 3.4 Feature Scaling
A **StandardScaler** (zero mean, unit variance) was applied to all 26 features. The scaler was **fit only on training data** and applied to validation/test data to prevent data leakage. The fitted scaler is saved as [scaler_final.pkl](file:///c:/Users/HYPER%20Computers/Downloads/a4.project.bilstm/scaler_final.pkl) for use during live inference.

### 3.5 Sequence Construction (Sliding Window)
For each geographic location, a **sliding window** of:
- **Sequence length = 6** (6 past hourly observations)
- **Forecast horizon = 2** (predict the cloudburst event 2 hours ahead)

This means: given atmospheric conditions at hours t−5, t−4, t−3, t−2, t−1, t, the model predicts whether a cloudburst will occur at hour **t+2**. This 2-hour lead time is operationally useful for early warning.

