## 6. Training Strategy — Rolling Window Cross-Validation

To avoid **data leakage** and simulate real-world deployment conditions, a **temporal rolling validation** strategy was used instead of random cross-validation:

| Window | Train Years | Validation Years |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | *(none)* | 2014, 2015 |
| 2 | 2014, 2015 | 2016, 2017 |
| 3 | 2014–2017 | 2020 |
| 4 | 2014–2020 | 2021 |
| 5 | 2014–2021 | 2022 |

**Note:** Years 2018–2019 appear to be missing from the dataset (possibly due to data availability). Year **2023 was held out entirely** as the unseen final test set.

Each window ensures the model is always trained on past data and validated on future data — exactly how a real forecasting model would be used.

### Optimization Metric: PR-AUC (Precision-Recall AUC)
Because the dataset is highly imbalanced, **ROC-AUC alone is misleading** (even bad models can score high). **PR-AUC** (Area Under the Precision-Recall Curve) is a far more informative metric for imbalanced problems and was used as the primary optimization target.

---

## 7. Hyperparameter Tuning

**30 trials of random search** were conducted, each evaluating a candidate hyperparameter set using rolling window cross-validation and computing the average validation PR-AUC across all windows. The search space was:

| Parameter | Options |
|---|---|
| LSTM Units | 32, 64, 128 |
| Dropout | 0.2, 0.3, 0.4, 0.5 |
| Dense Units | 16, 32, 48, 64 |
| Learning Rate | 1e-4, 5e-4, 1e-3, 5e-3, 1e-2 |

**Best average validation PR-AUC across 30 trials: 0.4375** (Trial 14)

The full search took approximately **3 hours** of compute time.

